<img src="http://www.bloodcircle.com/zariussig.jpg"></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#353535><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub5.ezboard.com/bbloodcircle.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=treenaspiritwolf>Treena Spiritwolf</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 6<br> <font color=#FF0000>(9/7/01 9:17:31 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub5.ezboard.com/fbloodcirclebloodcirclegeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1454.topic&index=20>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Dark Age of Camelot</span><hr size=1> I have checked up on this game to see what was so awesome about it . I know my opinion means nothing to any of you but honestly I really don't see how this game could be more interesting than EQ . I miss seeing all of you guys on !! I have to agree wit Jur 100% though !!!!!!  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#1E1E1E><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub5.ezboard.com/ussymbiant.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Ssymbiant</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_thatch.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 186<br> <font color=#FF0000>(9/7/01 11:56:28 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub5.ezboard.com/fbloodcirclebloodcirclegeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1454.topic&index=21>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Dark Age of Camelot</span><hr size=1> This is a lot of reading...I know, I know, you all expect that whenever you see the &quot;Ssymbiant&quot; tag...however, this article holds a lot of information that may help answer some questions as to my interest in this game.  Pay close attention to the &quot;Guilds&quot; and the part about &quot;Group oriented play&quot; section of this Review... Soul<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
Let me start by saying that DAoC has some pretty big shoes to jump into. The MMORPG genre has grown since the days of Ultima Online being released. Everquest came along and added 3D graphics and addictive gameplay to the genre. Anarchy Online came along and added single player capability and directed PvP (rather than free for all like in UO) to the mix. For DAoC to be successful, Mythic needs to make it in a way that will draw people away from those already existing games, and make them want to enter their world. <br>
<br>
Mythic has had some things going for them since early on. The setting itself makes many people more interested in the game. What other game offers youthe chance to walk around through the infamous city of Camelot? Kind of makes you wonder why no one grabbed this franchise yet eh? Being its public domain. <br>
<br>
By now you must be eager to get some hard facts, lets get to them! <br>
<br>
Artwork - Ah eye candy. To be honest this is one thing that has always drawn me to a game, and I know many other people as well. Well you wont be disappointed to find out that DAoC has enough eye candy to satisfy your needs. Their skydome is magnificent, clouds flowing in the breeze, sunsets and sunrises coloring it as far as your virtual eye can see. Nothing like cresting a hill and noticing a small quaint village below, or the path to Camelot near Humberton... oh my. You can expect more of those sights since the landscapes are done very well, their terrain is fleshed out by having small imperfections and brush over it. In Midgaard you can walk under the shadow of high, snow-covered mountains and in Albion you can see for miles in the Salisbury plains, and there are more locations in the world just as breathtaking to behold. <br>
<br>
Mythic has done a great job with the artwork and the general world in their game, and I imagine many new players will find themselves stopping just to look around, like I found myself doing. <br>
<br>
Models and skins are all done quite well. Each realm has different models they use, though in some cases they can be quite similar or even reused, so that you can have similar monsters of varying level power. The player characters are done very well, upon creation you have the opportunity to choose your race, and several attributes about your character to give it it's own unique look and feel, add to that also the opportunity to later customize your armor by use of various dyes and you can make yourself look even more unique. <br>
<br>
Gameplay - Probably the most important part of a game, after all the pretty pictures have become common, what keeps the DAoC dweller coming back? How fun the game is to play of course, and that will vary depending on what you expect to find. If you're a hardcore FPS guy, who hated Everquest and think Anarchy Online sucks, well to be honest, I don't think you should be reading this review, wait for PlanetSide instead. However if you like MMORPGs, this is right up your alley. <br>
<br>
DAoC is a group oriented game, but hey, don't start groaning yet, solo play is actually an option. While you will find better rewards grouping, soloing can be perfect for those days which you have an hour or so to log in and play, in which you will be able to gain some experience, money or tradeskill points. Encounters vary if you are grouped (meaning you form a band withother players) or going alone, monsters will be more difficult when grouped, making every fight difficult and gratifying when you win on the other hand if you are mano-a-mano you will find the fights much easier in an area than they are for a group. Either way, fighting wont be boring and the game caters to your availability and mood instead of forcing its preferences on you. <br>
<br>
For EQ/AC/AO players little has changed in advancement, you are still required to gain experience to gain levels, upon which you get skill points that you can use to increase your current available skills, some of those only become available at higher levels. Lastly the level also can determine which armor you may wear, something that is also restricted by class, can you say bye-bye twinking (where a high level player gives equipment to a low lever player which he would not have access to)? More on twinking later on this review. But despair not, for there are two ways to gain experience, either by the myriad of quests available at all levels. That will range from the standard deliver item a to person b, passing by some which you have to find and slay a beast to the more intricate ones requiring many steps before they are done.Or by killing mobs for experience be it in a group or solo as mentioned earlier. <br>
<br>
Mob killing too is similar in DAoC to other games. When you target a mob it's name appears in your box that displays the name of what you have currently targeted.The name is color coded to tell you how difficult the mob is for your level. Grey being so easy that you will not even receive experience or loot for killing it, all the way to purple, which tells you that the mob is entirely too high for your level. Also when clicking on the mob, your text box will be updated with a line telling you if the mob is aggressive or not. <br>
<br>
PvP - You could spend your entire life in the game, killing monsters, doing quests, and working on tradeskills, if that makes you happy. But there is something deeper to the world, and it comes in this side, the Player versus Player. Or should I say Realm versus Realm. <br>
<br>
When you first start your character, you will have to pick a race from one of three realms. Albion which has all human races, and is the home of Camelot itself. Midgard, where you have Trolls, Kobolds, and Dwarves in addition to the one human race called Norsemen. And last there is Hibernia, with it's Firbolgs, Elves, Lurikeens, and one human race. Each realm is one faction in this three way war between realms. <br>
<br>
The player conflicts are level based, this way the lower level players are protected from attacks by players who out level them by far. Also there is no PvP within your own realm, so no needing to worry about grief players on your side attacking you. <br>
<br>
What makes PvP so great in DAoC? Well it is not just running around and attacking each other. There are Keeps for you to conquer and claiming one for your realm means all the NPC guards residing in that keep will be converted and serve your side. There are battlements for archers to stand at, plugging arrows at the raiding masses below. Great doors to be opened,and within which you could have your army of melee types waiting. The mighty battles that you've seen in movies like Braveheart and the Messenger actually have the ability to happen here. You could be a part of it. <br>
<br>
Tradeskills - I keep mentioning those tradeskills. Old fans of UO are especially curious I am sure for, frankly, no game has come close to UO in this paticular area and because of this in other recent games tradeskills have not had much use really. This changes now. Player crafted items are among the best items in the game, better than the items you can buy in stores, and those with high tradeskills can repair items, as well as salvage material from otherwise useless items to use in your tradeskills practice. <br>
<br>
Finally someone goes back to the root of UO as well as you do not need to level to increase your tradeskills, this is a point most games missed, forcing the tradesman to go to combat to get better at his craft, I fail to see how the delicate hands of a crafter would be useful in battle, and apparently so does Mythic. You can play this game as a merchant, and be quite successful. Your base class will determine which tradeskills you can master, and from all your options you can only master in one. Also a system is in place that allows you to make some money while working on your trade skills, so that you can continue to work on them without having to go kill mobs for money. <br>
<br>
The level based restrictions in game for wearing guild emblems even have atradeskill counterpart. So that a level 1 tradesperson who has high smithing skill can also emblazon a shield or cloak with their guilds crest (read further). <br>
<br>
Guilds - Expect to see that line over your head like in other worlds. But that is not the only way you will recognize a guildmember. You can, once you reach a certain level or tradeskill skill, put your guild's emblem and colors on a shield or cloak. This allowing you to spot a fellow guild brethren from ever further off. <br>
<br>
In a guild one of the advantages for sure is the guild chat system, as seen onother games, where you can chat with other members without having to be grouped or near them. It is even the nice pleasant green color seen in EverQuest by default, so you can once again enjoy the infamous 'green spam'. <br>
<br>
Another benefit are the ranks you can define. This way you the Leadership can determine who in the guild has what powers and responsibilities. <br>
<br>
Twinks and Cheaters - Many don't like twinking, and no one likes a cheater.These issues have been addressed. For twinking, well it's not going to do you much good, you see, items are categorized and even have colored cons like monsters do. If you are using an item intended for someone of higher level, you won't get the all the properties of it. Armor won't protect you as much as it would if you were the appropriate level to wear it, and weapons will not hit as hard. Also since the item is so far above yourlevel, you will be using it incorrectly, causing it to wear out sooner then it really should. While one could still twink with money, that is not going to be putting people at a great advantage of other people at their level. As for cheating. Well it is my understanding that when the game goes live, you will only be able to choose one realm to play in. Once you are in that realm, all your characters will need to be. That should hopefully curb most forms of spy cheating, where people log in a character from another realm to determine where they are located. <br>
<br>
And notice as well that the Dev team during beta has been quite responsive to fixing bugs quickly, I believe that we'll see this continue past release. Mythic has always ruled with a fair hand during beta too, so I think exploiters will be handled quickly and quietly as they should be, only time can tell on this one though. <br>
<br>
Summary - Well to conclude, I think the folks at Mythic Entertainment have built a game that is the next step in the right direction of the MMORPG genre. So certain of this that I have already pre-ordered it for I trust they have learned from their roots. From the tradeskills system that allows people to be merchants like UO tothe addictive gameplay that keeps people wanting to advance like EQ and theaddition of not just PvP, but something I can only think of to call 'EpicPvP'.Dark Age of Camelot comes across overall as a good solid game, that has been surprisingly stable throughout beta. I definitely think that if you are a fan of the MMORPG Fantasy Genre you should buy Dark Age of Camelot when it is released in October.<br>
